Garbage collection, and image scanning.

Two operational concerns keep a registry healthy over time: reclaiming space, and knowing what's inside your images.

First, garbage collection. A registry running for months accumulates thousands of blobs: layers for tags that were overwritten, or images nobody references anymore. Garbage collection sweeps them. For registry-two, you run its garbage-collect command, with dash dash delete-untagged. What it does is: walk all the manifests in storage, walk all the blobs those manifests reference, and then delete any blob that isn't referenced. With delete-untagged, it also removes manifests with no tag, which are the none images you see in docker images. Storage grows surprisingly fast; a continuous-integration pipeline pushing one image per commit can accumulate a multi-gigabyte registry within a quarter. So garbage collection, plus a retention policy, like, keep the last ten tags, or, delete non-production builds older than thirty days, is essential. On Harbor and the cloud registries, you don't run this by hand; you configure those retention rules, and it happens for you.

Second, image scanning. Modern registries, Hub, e-c-r, g-h-c-r, Harbor, Quay, scan pushed images against vulnerability databases, and flag known issues by severity. You can also scan locally, with tools like trivy or gripe. They produce a list, for example, a total of forty-seven vulnerabilities, with some high and one critical.

Teams act on this in two common ways. A continuous-integration gate fails a build that introduces a new high or critical vulnerability. And admission control, with tools like Kyverno or o-p-a Gatekeeper, refuses to schedule unscanned or vulnerable images in Kubernetes. Scanning is the detection half of supply-chain hygiene; it tells you what's vulnerable. Reducing the surface area, with smaller bases, non-root users, distroless images, and dropped capabilities, is the other half, and it's exactly where module eight goes next.
